30
00:02:21,960 --> 00:02:26,800
about all the things we don't understand about the mind,

31
00:02:26,800 --> 00:02:31,040
which is almost everything.

32
00:02:31,040 --> 00:02:36,800
And the first discussion is, well, the whole chapter

33
00:02:36,800 --> 00:02:40,360
is making fun of the most popular ideas.

34
00:02:40,360 --> 00:02:43,780
And the most popular idea of the mind

35
00:02:43,780 --> 00:02:50,280
is that people think that they're not doing the thinking,

36
00:02:50,280 --> 00:02:54,280
but there's something inside them that's doing the thinking.

37
00:02:54,280 --> 00:02:59,440
And this idea that there is a self

38
00:02:59,440 --> 00:03:05,800
is embedded in just about everything we say and think.

39
00:03:05,800 --> 00:03:09,200
And really, it's hard to see how you would do without it.

40
00:03:09,200 --> 00:03:14,680
But if you ask, what is the self,

41
00:03:14,680 --> 00:03:17,800
then since this idea is so popular,

42
00:03:17,800 --> 00:03:21,160
people begin to believe that there is such a thing,

43
00:03:21,160 --> 00:03:24,380
and it takes all sorts of various forms.

44
00:03:24,380 --> 00:03:28,220
And the most dangerous form, maybe,

45
00:03:28,220 --> 00:03:32,460
is the one that religions exploit,

46
00:03:32,460 --> 00:03:37,620
which is that inside a person with all their complications,

47
00:03:37,620 --> 00:03:40,940
there's a little pure essence called the soul, or the self,

48
00:03:40,940 --> 00:03:43,660
or whatever you want to call it.

49
00:03:43,660 --> 00:03:48,860
And it's impossible to describe it or explain it

50
00:03:48,860 --> 00:03:49,900
in physical terms.

51
00:03:49,900 --> 00:04:00,200
And so that is one of the reasons why we think there are

52
00:04:00,200 --> 00:04:07,060
two worlds, a physical world and lots of other kinds of worlds.

53
00:04:07,060 --> 00:04:12,640
Each of us has some imaginary model of what they are

54
00:04:12,640 --> 00:04:13,600
and what they're in.

55
00:04:20,340 --> 00:04:24,900
And philosophers talk about it and existentialists and so on.

56
00:04:24,900 --> 00:04:27,860
So there are lots of problems about our ideas,

57
00:04:27,860 --> 00:04:29,460
about ourselves.

58
00:04:29,460 --> 00:04:36,460
And in reading around for half my life,

59
00:04:36,460 --> 00:04:42,180
I was puzzled at the strange ideas that are around.

60
00:04:42,180 --> 00:04:49,060
And in Aristotle, I find the first intelligible theories

61
00:04:49,060 --> 00:04:51,020
of mind and emotions.

62
00:04:51,020 --> 00:04:54,460
So if you look at particular Aristotle's,

63
00:04:54,460 --> 00:04:56,500
there are a number of books.

64
00:04:56,500 --> 00:04:59,340
And one of them is called Rhetoric.

65
00:04:59,340 --> 00:05:04,460
And it's full of theories about how people reason and influence

66
00:05:04,460 --> 00:05:05,020
each other.

67
00:05:05,020 --> 00:05:15,180
And I'll show you some quotes from that.

68
00:05:15,180 --> 00:05:17,020
Because when I look at the history

69
00:05:17,020 --> 00:05:21,700
that I've encountered about psychology,

70
00:05:21,700 --> 00:05:27,020
Aristotle stands out as being the first and among the best.

71
00:05:27,020 --> 00:05:31,540
And as far as I can see, there were no psychologists nearly

72
00:05:31,540 --> 00:05:33,140
as good as him.

73
00:05:33,140 --> 00:05:37,500
Of course, we don't know whether there was a him exactly.

74
00:05:37,500 --> 00:05:41,100
Because what we have of Aristotle,

75
00:05:41,100 --> 00:05:43,960
and there's a lot of writing, but it's all cobbled together

76
00:05:43,960 --> 00:05:48,160
by students from all sorts of manuscripts by other people,

77
00:05:48,160 --> 00:05:49,720
and people who took notes.

78
00:05:49,720 --> 00:05:55,360
And Aristotle claims to have learned a lot from Plato.

79
00:05:55,360 --> 00:06:00,400
We have very little writing from him.

80
00:06:00,400 --> 00:06:04,880
And so there you go three centuries

81
00:06:04,880 --> 00:06:09,600
before the Christian era, as it's called.

82
00:06:09,600 --> 00:06:13,960
And then a couple of thousand years later,

83
00:06:13,960 --> 00:06:23,320
you start to find people like Spinoza, and Kant, and John

84
00:06:23,320 --> 00:06:29,120
Locke, and David Hume, who start to make psychology theories,

85
00:06:29,120 --> 00:06:34,760
very little of which is as good as the ones that Aristotle

86
00:06:34,760 --> 00:06:37,200
has in all his fragments.

87
00:06:37,200 --> 00:06:39,760
So one question that frequently bothers me,

88
00:06:39,760 --> 00:06:45,320
and it should bother everyone, is why did science

89
00:06:45,320 --> 00:06:48,600
disappear for 1,000 years?

90
00:06:48,600 --> 00:06:53,840
And the standard explanation is the rise

91
00:06:53,840 --> 00:06:59,360
of the great religions, and why did it come back?

92
00:06:59,360 --> 00:07:02,880
And you see with the first signs of anything

93
00:07:02,880 --> 00:07:06,760
like modern science, at least in my view,

94
00:07:06,760 --> 00:07:08,920
with Galileo and Newton, there are

95
00:07:08,920 --> 00:07:11,640
a couple of people before that.

96
00:07:11,640 --> 00:07:15,000
There are some people in the Muslim world

97
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:17,840
who invented some high school algebra,

98
00:07:17,840 --> 00:07:20,880
and they make a big fuss about that.

99
00:07:20,880 --> 00:07:25,780
It looks like Archimedes, in a very recently discovered

100
00:07:25,780 --> 00:07:30,760
manuscript, computed an integral.

101
00:07:30,760 --> 00:07:34,520
He found the volume of a cone, which is, what is it?

102
00:07:35,240 --> 00:07:39,720
Sixth BH, I forget.

103
00:07:39,720 --> 00:07:46,400
Anyway, so why did science disappear?

104
00:07:46,400 --> 00:07:48,640
And why did psychology appear so late?

105
00:07:48,640 --> 00:07:53,520
Because there isn't much psychology in the modern sense

106
00:07:53,520 --> 00:07:59,840
until 1900, or the late 1800s, with Francis Galton

107
00:07:59,840 --> 00:08:05,560
and William James lived around here,

108
00:08:05,560 --> 00:08:16,320
and Rudolf Fleiss, Sigmund Freud, starts writing in 1895.

109
00:08:16,320 --> 00:08:21,240
People make fun of Freud, as I mentioned last week.

110
00:08:21,240 --> 00:08:26,920
But in fact, among other things, how many of you

111
00:08:26,920 --> 00:08:29,200
have read the recent criticisms of Freud,

112
00:08:29,200 --> 00:08:32,000
which claim that he was a complete faker

113
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:36,120
and never cured a single patient?

114
00:08:36,120 --> 00:08:37,880
This is popular stuff.

115
00:08:37,880 --> 00:08:39,640
I don't believe Freud ever really

116
00:08:39,640 --> 00:08:43,360
claimed to cure a single patient.

117
00:08:43,360 --> 00:08:47,480
So the critics, who are really very ferocious,

118
00:08:47,480 --> 00:08:51,200
claim that he made up all his data and so forth.

119
00:08:51,200 --> 00:08:55,920
But most of what Freud says is that psychoanalysis

120
00:08:55,920 --> 00:08:59,940
might be a good way to find out what you're really thinking

121
00:08:59,940 --> 00:09:03,720
and discover more about yourself and your goals and so forth.

