And if not, why not?

170
00:12:28,720 --> 00:12:35,920
So here's a list of typical situations,

171
00:12:35,920 --> 00:12:43,640
grieving for a lost child, panic at being in an enclosed space.

172
00:12:43,640 --> 00:12:47,760
I'm not sure any of the words in the list of 300 standard

173
00:12:47,760 --> 00:12:50,600
emotions are good enough to describe

174
00:12:50,600 --> 00:12:57,560
how you feel for any of these not unusual states.

175
00:12:57,560 --> 00:13:02,240
Have you ever lost control of your car at high speed?

176
00:13:02,240 --> 00:13:04,100
No, but when I first learned to drive,

177
00:13:04,100 --> 00:13:07,640
I couldn't believe that you could read signs at the same

178
00:13:07,640 --> 00:13:08,280
time as.

179
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:22,440
Well, anyway, one of the very best psychologists in history,

180
00:13:22,440 --> 00:13:28,040
or pair of psychologists, aren't even called psychologists.

181
00:13:28,040 --> 00:13:33,840
These are two guys named Conrad Lorenz and Nico Tinbergen.

182
00:13:33,840 --> 00:13:37,080
And somebody made up the word ethology.

183
00:13:37,080 --> 00:13:40,520
What they study is the behavior of animals.

184
00:13:40,520 --> 00:13:42,880
And in some sense, presumably, they're

185
00:13:42,880 --> 00:13:44,960
studying the psychology of animals

186
00:13:44,960 --> 00:13:52,080
because just as with a person, when somebody flies into a rage,

187
00:13:52,080 --> 00:13:54,080
you're not describing their mental state.

188
00:13:54,080 --> 00:13:57,840
You're describing something about how they behave.

189
00:13:57,840 --> 00:14:01,120
And so the ethologists, too, are psychologists.

190
00:14:01,120 --> 00:14:08,280
And Tinbergen and Lorenz, starting around 1920s,

191
00:14:08,280 --> 00:14:12,840
started to analyze the behavior of animals in great detail.

192
00:14:12,840 --> 00:14:20,280
And so here's an example of how a certain fish behaves.

193
00:14:22,480 --> 00:14:24,240
I actually forgot which fish it is,

194
00:14:24,240 --> 00:14:28,360
but there's a picture of it in the book.

195
00:14:28,360 --> 00:14:33,320
And at different points in its life,

196
00:14:33,320 --> 00:14:35,560
it's in different phases.

197
00:14:35,560 --> 00:14:39,000
And this is just one diagram of a dozen

198
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:45,360
for this particular fish and its reproduction, which

199
00:14:45,360 --> 00:14:50,860
involves an environment with plants and other things.

200
00:14:50,860 --> 00:14:54,580
And it divides its behavior into parenting, courtship,

201
00:14:54,580 --> 00:14:56,860
nesting, and fighting.

202
00:14:56,860 --> 00:15:02,340
And then you see each of those as a lot of subdivisions.

203
00:15:02,340 --> 00:15:07,560
And Tinbergen and Lorenz and some students

204
00:15:07,560 --> 00:15:10,980
discovered all these things by sitting in front of fish tanks

205
00:15:10,980 --> 00:15:15,260
and watching the fish for months and years.

206
00:15:15,260 --> 00:15:24,220
Tinbergen also spent years on some beach watching seagulls.

207
00:15:24,220 --> 00:15:26,780
And so he has a diagram like this

208
00:15:26,780 --> 00:15:31,900
for a particular class of seagulls.

209
00:15:34,580 --> 00:15:41,900
When I came to Boston, my friends and I

210
00:15:41,900 --> 00:15:46,740
used to go to Nahant and look at these tide pools

211
00:15:46,740 --> 00:15:49,420
there, where there are a lot of activities.

212
00:15:49,420 --> 00:15:51,260
And it was very interesting.

213
00:15:51,260 --> 00:15:54,260
And I got a big fish tank and imported

214
00:15:54,260 --> 00:15:56,960
all sorts of little animals and plants

215
00:15:56,960 --> 00:16:01,020
from the tide pools in Nahant.

216
00:16:01,020 --> 00:16:03,700
And I watched them for about a year and didn't learn anything.

217
00:16:04,620 --> 00:16:12,100
And that was before I read Tinbergen.

218
00:16:12,100 --> 00:16:15,180
And then I realized there's something

219
00:16:15,180 --> 00:16:18,540
about those people, which is they could watch a fish

220
00:16:18,540 --> 00:16:21,140
and recognize all sorts of behaviors.

221
00:16:21,140 --> 00:16:23,900
And I would just watch a fish and wonder whether it was hungry

222
00:16:23,900 --> 00:16:25,940
or what.

223
00:16:25,940 --> 00:16:29,700
Wouldn't you get bored swimming back and forth for three years

224
00:16:29,700 --> 00:16:32,340
in this?

225
00:16:32,340 --> 00:16:37,860
Anyway, so here are the great psychologists of our day,

226
00:16:37,860 --> 00:16:44,260
Aristotle 2,000 years ago, and Lorentz and Tinbergen

227
00:16:44,260 --> 00:16:53,460
in the 1930s, and Sigmund Freud and Galton and William James

228
00:16:53,460 --> 00:16:56,100
around 1900.

229
00:16:56,100 --> 00:16:58,660
And then what went wrong?

230
00:16:58,660 --> 00:17:00,620
There's almost no good psychology

231
00:17:00,620 --> 00:17:05,420
between then and 1950s, when something called cognitive

232
00:17:05,420 --> 00:17:07,860
psychology started.

233
00:17:07,860 --> 00:17:14,060
And it was partly due to people who said,

234
00:17:14,060 --> 00:17:17,060
let's make psychology more scientific.

235
00:17:17,060 --> 00:17:20,980
And you've probably all heard of Pavlov or Watson.

236
00:17:20,980 --> 00:17:26,260
And what happened is around 1900, some psychologists said,

237
00:17:26,260 --> 00:17:29,780
well, these Galton's and Freud's and William James

238
00:17:29,780 --> 00:17:33,100
are very poetic and expressive and literary.

239
00:17:33,100 --> 00:17:38,180
And they write much better than we do and tells good stories.

240
00:17:38,180 --> 00:17:39,500
But they're not scientists.

241
00:17:39,500 --> 00:17:42,500
And they don't do reproducible experiments.

242
00:17:42,500 --> 00:17:45,020
So what we have to do is simplify the situation

243
00:17:45,020 --> 00:17:48,060
to find the basic laws of behavior.

244
00:17:48,060 --> 00:17:52,780
So let's take a pigeon and put it in a vacuum in the dark.

245
00:17:52,780 --> 00:17:58,420
Well, they didn't go that far.

246
00:17:58,420 --> 00:18:00,860
But they did put it in the dark.

247
00:18:00,860 --> 00:18:05,980
And there were two illuminated levers to work.

248
00:18:05,980 --> 00:18:07,340
And you could make a sound.

249
00:18:07,340 --> 00:18:10,740
And the sound could be very annoying.

250
00:18:10,740 --> 00:18:14,620
Or you could have a bright, annoying flashing

251
00:18:14,620 --> 00:18:16,420
light or something.

252
00:18:16,420 --> 00:18:18,780
And the animal would push one of two levers.

253
00:18:18,780 --> 00:18:24,060
And one of them would make the stimulus even more annoying.

254
00:18:24,060 --> 00:18:27,300
And one of them would make it go away.

255
00:18:27,300 --> 00:18:31,380
And you'd plot curves of how often the animal pressed

256
00:18:31,380 --> 00:18:32,300
these levers.

257
00:18:32,300 --> 00:18:36,620
So you would get a quantitative theory of how much it learned

258
00:18:36,620 --> 00:18:39,460
and how much it could remember and how many trials it

259
00:18:39,460 --> 00:18:40,260
would have to do.

260
00:18:43,020 --> 00:18:46,900
Then instead of just looking at reactions to stimuli,

261
00:18:46,900 --> 00:18:52,100
they quickly switched to trying to teach the animal things

262
00:18:52,100 --> 00:18:57,260
by giving it two alternatives, turn left or turn right

263
00:18:57,780 --> 00:19:00,820
or push this button or that or whatever.

264
00:19:00,820 --> 00:19:03,100
And if they pushed the one you approve of,

265
00:19:03,100 --> 00:19:06,420
then you'd give them a little pellet of food.

266
00:19:06,420 --> 00:19:07,780
And there was a lot of engineering

267
00:19:07,780 --> 00:19:11,420
so that you would make sure that the food got to them

268
00:19:11,420 --> 00:19:12,020
right away.

269
00:19:12,020 --> 00:19:15,340
Because if there were a 10-second delay

270
00:19:15,340 --> 00:19:19,300
between an action and a reward, the pigeon or a squirrel

271
00:19:19,300 --> 00:19:24,020
or a rat or a cat or a dog would learn much less quickly

272
00:19:24,020 --> 00:19:26,900
than if there was a one-second delay.

273
00:19:26,900 --> 00:19:34,220
And anyway, that went on for 50 years, starting around 1900,

274
00:19:34,220 --> 00:19:36,500
Pavlov and his dogs.

275
00:19:36,500 --> 00:19:40,580
And there's a great movie that some guy came around with

276
00:19:40,580 --> 00:19:43,980
that had been taken of Pavlov's lab.

277
00:19:43,980 --> 00:19:50,300
And it shows sort of like a great dictator or something.

278
00:19:50,300 --> 00:19:53,820
There's this room with a lot of cages and dogs and mostly

279
00:19:53,820 --> 00:19:55,580
dogs in this case.

280
00:19:55,580 --> 00:19:56,940
And Pavlov comes in, and there are

281
00:19:56,940 --> 00:19:59,740
a bunch of lackeys who sort of bow and scrape

282
00:19:59,740 --> 00:20:01,780
because he's a lord.

283
00:20:01,780 --> 00:20:04,500
And he comes in, and all the dogs

284
00:20:04,500 --> 00:20:09,060
run into the corner of their cage and yelp.

285
00:20:09,060 --> 00:20:15,020
So the Pavlovians tried pretty hard

286
00:20:15,020 --> 00:20:17,340
to get that movie suppressed.

287
00:20:17,340 --> 00:20:19,740
And I haven't seen it in recent years.

288
00:20:20,180 --> 00:20:31,820
But anyway, Fred Skinner, who was a professor when

289
00:20:31,820 --> 00:20:36,060
I was an undergraduate at Harvard,

290
00:20:36,060 --> 00:20:39,660
was the first one to really automate

291
00:20:39,660 --> 00:20:41,620
this experimental psychology.

292
00:20:41,620 --> 00:20:44,380
And he invented what's called a Skinner box,

293
00:20:44,380 --> 00:20:49,220
but it's just a soundproof, lightproof, well-ventilated

294
00:20:49,220 --> 00:20:52,500
and thermally regulated cage.

295
00:20:52,500 --> 00:20:54,340
And you can put a rat or a pigeon.

296
00:20:54,340 --> 00:20:58,180
Those are the most common animals.

297
00:20:58,180 --> 00:21:00,500
They're very inexpensive because they're free.

298
00:21:03,820 --> 00:21:05,660
No one knows much about dolphins.

299
00:21:05,660 --> 00:21:13,900
They've been studied for 50 years.

300
00:21:13,900 --> 00:21:16,980
Whenever John Watts's name, remember

301
00:21:16,980 --> 00:21:18,420
the name of the great dolphin?

302
00:21:21,300 --> 00:21:23,740
Lily, thanks.

303
00:21:23,740 --> 00:21:26,820
He discovered a lot about dolphins

304
00:21:26,820 --> 00:21:31,100
and a certain amount about their communication

305
00:21:31,100 --> 00:21:33,940
and a little bit about whales.

306
00:21:33,940 --> 00:21:37,140
But there's an interesting mystery.

307
00:21:37,140 --> 00:21:42,900
I forget which whales, but some whales have a 20-minute song.

308
00:21:42,900 --> 00:21:44,820
And they repeat it for a whole season.

309
00:21:44,820 --> 00:21:48,660
And next year, that song is a little bit different.

310
00:21:48,660 --> 00:21:50,820
But it goes essentially without repeating.

311
00:21:50,820 --> 00:21:54,420
It's very complicated for 20 minutes.

312
00:21:54,420 --> 00:21:57,100
And people have studied that a lot.

313
00:21:57,100 --> 00:21:59,980
And no one has the slightest idea of what it means.

314
00:22:03,340 --> 00:22:06,940
And nobody even has any good conjectures, which bothers me.

315
00:22:06,940 --> 00:22:10,100
What I think it probably means is this.

316
00:22:10,100 --> 00:22:12,020
When there's a whole bunch of fish somewhere

317
00:22:12,020 --> 00:22:18,220
for one of these whales, it might be 200 miles away.

318
00:22:18,220 --> 00:22:20,900
Whales eat a lot.

319
00:22:20,900 --> 00:22:24,580
And it's very important to find where the fish are.

320
00:22:24,580 --> 00:22:30,740
And I believe this message, which

321
00:22:30,740 --> 00:22:34,980
changes a bit during the season, might be telling you

322
00:22:34,980 --> 00:22:40,420
where the food is on the Atlantic or Pacific coastline

323
00:22:40,420 --> 00:22:41,900
in great detail.

324
00:22:41,900 --> 00:22:46,340
Because if somebody finds a lot of fish somewhere,

325
00:22:46,340 --> 00:22:48,100
you have to swim 300 miles.

326
00:22:48,100 --> 00:22:50,900
And if they're not there.

327
00:22:50,900 --> 00:22:54,780
So anyway, it's interesting that John Lilly got a lot

328
00:22:54,780 --> 00:22:59,020
of publicity, but he didn't discover squat.

329
00:22:59,020 --> 00:23:04,780
And finally, the dolphin study years

330
00:23:04,780 --> 00:23:07,240
gave up because nothing happened.

331
00:23:07,240 --> 00:23:09,940
Anybody have heard anything?

332
00:23:09,940 --> 00:23:13,620
I haven't paid any attention for 20 years.

333
00:23:13,620 --> 00:23:15,540
Have you heard of anybody discovering anything

334
00:23:15,540 --> 00:23:17,440
about dolphins?

335
00:23:17,440 --> 00:23:19,060
Except they're very good at solving

336
00:23:19,060 --> 00:23:20,660
a lot of physical problems.

337
00:23:26,800 --> 00:23:33,060
Anyway, I'm bothered by the mystery

338
00:23:33,060 --> 00:23:39,780
of why was there some psychology in Aristotle's time.

339
00:23:39,780 --> 00:23:47,220
And why didn't it get anywhere till 1950

340
00:23:47,220 --> 00:23:50,540
when there was regular psychology?

341
00:23:50,540 --> 00:23:54,660
But it was afflicted by what I call physics envy.

342
00:23:54,660 --> 00:23:57,260
Namely, you run into people like Estes.

343
00:23:57,260 --> 00:23:59,620
And well, he was pretty good, actually.

344
00:23:59,620 --> 00:24:03,220
But there are a lot of psychologists who made up

345
00:24:03,220 --> 00:24:07,460
things like Maxwell's equations for how animals learn.

346
00:24:07,460 --> 00:24:10,420
And there were generally three or four laws.

347
00:24:10,420 --> 00:24:16,020
And if there's a sequence of events,

348
00:24:16,020 --> 00:24:20,820
then animals remember a lot about the first few

349
00:24:20,820 --> 00:24:23,140
and the last few in the sequence.

350
00:24:23,140 --> 00:24:25,460
They don't remember much about the middle.

351
00:24:25,460 --> 00:24:29,760
And of course, the reliability of their memory

352
00:24:29,760 --> 00:24:32,460
depends a lot on how recent it was

353
00:24:32,460 --> 00:24:36,080
and on how powerful the reward was and blah, blah, blah.

354
00:24:36,080 --> 00:24:38,920
And so they get these little sets of rules

355
00:24:38,920 --> 00:24:40,440
that look like Newton's laws.

356
00:24:40,440 --> 00:24:45,140
And that was the kind of sort of psychological physics

357
00:24:45,140 --> 00:24:50,440
that the so-called behaviorists were mostly looking for.

358
00:24:50,440 --> 00:24:54,680
This was not what Tinbergen and Lorentz did,

359
00:24:54,680 --> 00:24:57,400
because they wrote books with extensive descriptions

360
00:24:57,400 --> 00:25:02,280
of what the animals did and made little diagrammatic guesses

361
00:25:02,280 --> 00:25:05,120
about the structure of the subroutines

362
00:25:05,120 --> 00:25:08,720
and substructures.

363
00:25:08,720 --> 00:25:13,320
Anyway, end of history, but it's a nice question.

364
00:25:13,320 --> 00:25:14,960
Why do some sciences grow?

365
00:25:14,960 --> 00:25:21,200
And why was psychology just about the last one?

366
00:25:21,200 --> 00:25:24,040
I suspect it was it could have been earlier,

367
00:25:24,040 --> 00:25:27,520
but people tried to imitate the physicists

368
00:25:27,520 --> 00:25:30,640
and tried to say maybe there's something like Newton's

369
00:25:30,640 --> 00:25:34,640
or Maxwell's laws for the mind.

370
00:25:34,640 --> 00:25:38,000
And they found a few, but they weren't enough to explain much.

371
00:25:41,920 --> 00:25:43,240
So there are a lot of questions.

372
00:25:48,560 --> 00:25:51,260
When Seymour Papert and I started

373
00:25:51,260 --> 00:25:58,880
thinking about these things, which was really around 1960,

374
00:25:58,880 --> 00:26:06,020
I had been working on some ideas about AI in the late 50s.

375
00:26:06,020 --> 00:26:10,800
And my PhD thesis was a theory of neural networks,

376
00:26:10,800 --> 00:26:16,240
which was sort of interesting, but never really

377
00:26:16,240 --> 00:26:17,000
went anywhere.

378
00:26:19,840 --> 00:26:23,000
I went to a meeting in London somewhere

379
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:25,900
and gave a talk about a theory of learning

380
00:26:25,900 --> 00:26:29,420
that was based on some neural network ideas.

381
00:26:29,420 --> 00:26:33,420
And there was this person from South Africa

382
00:26:33,420 --> 00:26:39,100
named Seymour Papert who gave the same paper.

383
00:26:39,100 --> 00:26:45,340
And I hope this happens to you someday.

384
00:26:45,340 --> 00:26:49,460
Find somebody who thinks so much like you,

385
00:26:49,460 --> 00:26:52,700
only different enough that it's worth it

386
00:26:52,700 --> 00:26:56,500
and that you only have to say about three words a day

387
00:26:56,500 --> 00:27:01,020
and some whole new thing starts, because we really

388
00:27:01,020 --> 00:27:04,180
did write the same paper and it had the same equation in it.

389
00:27:09,820 --> 00:27:14,140
And he had been working for Piaget,

390
00:27:14,140 --> 00:27:17,100
who was the first great child psychologist.

391
00:27:17,100 --> 00:27:19,500
I should have mentioned Piaget, who probably

392
00:27:19,500 --> 00:27:22,500
discovered more things about psychology

393
00:27:22,500 --> 00:27:25,940
than any other single person in history.

394
00:27:25,940 --> 00:27:30,540
And there are lots of people now who say,

395
00:27:30,540 --> 00:27:37,100
he was wrong about 0.73, because children learned that

396
00:27:37,100 --> 00:27:41,180
at the age of 2 and 1 half instead of 2 and 3 quarters.

397
00:27:41,180 --> 00:27:44,460
I'm parodying the Piaget critic community,

398
00:27:44,460 --> 00:27:47,460
but it's pretty bad.

399
00:27:47,460 --> 00:27:52,300
And I think those poor guys are uncomfortable,

400
00:27:52,300 --> 00:27:57,020
because Jean Piaget published 20 books full of observations

401
00:27:57,020 --> 00:28:00,220
about children that, as far as I know,

402
00:28:00,220 --> 00:28:03,340
no one had made systematically before.

403
00:28:03,340 --> 00:28:09,260
And in his later years, he started

404
00:28:09,260 --> 00:28:13,140
courting algebraic mathematicians,

405
00:28:13,140 --> 00:28:16,100
because he wanted more formal theories.

406
00:28:16,100 --> 00:28:22,660
And in my view, he wanted to make his theories worse,

407
00:28:22,660 --> 00:28:25,060
and nothing much happened.

408
00:28:25,060 --> 00:28:28,580
But he did visit here a couple of times,

409
00:28:28,580 --> 00:28:34,220
and it was really exciting to meet

410
00:28:34,220 --> 00:28:36,220
the starter of a whole new field.

411
00:28:39,740 --> 00:28:45,620
Anyway, Papert and I discussed lots of things,

412
00:28:45,620 --> 00:28:51,380
and somehow or other, we kept finding more ideas

413
00:28:51,380 --> 00:28:52,700
about psychology.

414
00:28:52,700 --> 00:28:57,300
And it finally gelled into the idea that, well,

415
00:28:57,300 --> 00:28:59,100
if you look at the brain, you know

416
00:28:59,100 --> 00:29:02,620
that there are several hundred different brain centers.

417
00:29:02,620 --> 00:29:04,580
What's all that stuff for?

418
00:29:04,580 --> 00:29:09,420
And how could it possibly make any sense

419
00:29:09,420 --> 00:29:12,420
to try to explain what it does in terms

420
00:29:12,420 --> 00:29:16,540
of four laws like Newton?

421
00:29:16,540 --> 00:29:19,620
How does a car work?

422
00:29:19,620 --> 00:29:22,680
Is there a magical force inside the engine that

423
00:29:22,680 --> 00:29:25,020
causes the wheels to turn?

424
00:29:25,020 --> 00:29:27,540
No.

425
00:29:27,540 --> 00:29:29,700
There's this funny thing in the back

426
00:29:29,700 --> 00:29:32,620
to cause a differential, so that if the car isn't

427
00:29:32,620 --> 00:29:37,840
going in a straight line, the two wheels

428
00:29:37,840 --> 00:29:43,560
going at different speeds won't rip the.

429
00:29:43,560 --> 00:29:45,800
If the two wheels were going at the same speed,

430
00:29:45,800 --> 00:29:49,000
the tread would come off in five minutes.

431
00:29:49,000 --> 00:29:50,960
You ever wonder what a differential is for?

432
00:29:53,920 --> 00:29:57,720
So most of the car is fixing bugs in the other parts.

433
00:30:00,680 --> 00:30:04,040
Most of the brain is because we started out

434
00:30:04,040 --> 00:30:08,040
as fish or lizards or whatever you like.

435
00:30:08,040 --> 00:30:12,680
And making the brain bigger wouldn't

436
00:30:12,680 --> 00:30:17,080
help much because you'd just get a heavier lizard that

437
00:30:17,080 --> 00:30:21,640
had to eat more and would think more slowly.

438
00:30:21,640 --> 00:30:24,200
So size is bad.

439
00:30:24,200 --> 00:30:28,200
But on the other hand, if you need another cubic inch

440
00:30:28,200 --> 00:30:31,760
of brain to fix the bugs in the other part,

441
00:30:31,760 --> 00:30:41,720
then the evolutionary advantage of being smarter

442
00:30:41,720 --> 00:30:44,060
had better make you able to catch a little more

443
00:30:44,060 --> 00:30:45,760
food per hour.

444
00:30:45,760 --> 00:30:52,160
And so each person is an ecology of these different processes.

445
00:30:52,160 --> 00:31:00,000
And the brain reached its present size

446
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:02,160
about a million years ago, I guess.

447
00:31:02,160 --> 00:31:04,760
What's the current guess?

448
00:31:04,760 --> 00:31:06,480
Anybody been tracked?

449
00:31:06,480 --> 00:31:09,560
They keep discovering new ancestors of humans.

450
00:31:09,560 --> 00:31:13,160
And I don't have the patience to read about them

451
00:31:13,160 --> 00:31:16,360
because you know that next week somebody will say,

452
00:31:16,360 --> 00:31:19,000
oh, that isn't in the main line.

453
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:22,840
And you were just unlucky to discover that skeleton.

454
00:31:22,840 --> 00:31:37,800
So anyway, Papert and I and a lot of students

455
00:31:37,800 --> 00:31:41,920
gradually developed this picture that the mind is made

456
00:31:41,920 --> 00:31:45,280
of lots of processes or agents or resources

457
00:31:45,280 --> 00:31:47,640
or whatever you want to call them.

458
00:31:47,640 --> 00:31:50,600
And it's anybody's guess what they are.

459
00:31:50,600 --> 00:31:55,440
If you look at the anatomy of the brain,

460
00:31:55,440 --> 00:31:56,960
you know that people label regions.

461
00:31:56,960 --> 00:32:01,360
So it's very clear that this occipital lobe back here

462
00:32:01,360 --> 00:32:04,000
is largely concerned with vision.

463
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:10,800
But I forget where the one for hearing is.

464
00:32:10,800 --> 00:32:14,400
If you destroy the part of the brain

465
00:32:14,400 --> 00:32:18,440
for hearing in some animals, you get a little bit

466
00:32:18,440 --> 00:32:24,120
of increased function in some part of the visual system

467
00:32:24,120 --> 00:32:27,920
that seems to enable the animal to hear a little bit

468
00:32:27,920 --> 00:32:30,240
and make some reactions.

469
00:32:30,240 --> 00:32:36,200
And there's a whole lot of hype, I think you have to call it,

470
00:32:36,200 --> 00:32:39,240
about the flexibility of the nervous system.

471
00:32:39,240 --> 00:32:42,640
That is, if certain brain areas get destroyed,

472
00:32:42,640 --> 00:32:44,640
other parts take over.

473
00:32:44,640 --> 00:32:47,120
They almost never are as good.

474
00:32:47,120 --> 00:32:51,600
And mostly, many functions never get taken over at all

475
00:32:51,600 --> 00:32:56,280
but are replaced by ones that superficially seem similar.

476
00:32:56,280 --> 00:33:00,400
And so there's a whole lot of, I guess,

477
00:33:00,400 --> 00:33:04,400
wishful thinking that the brain is immensely resourceful

478
00:33:04,400 --> 00:33:07,680
and error-correcting and repairing.

479
00:33:07,680 --> 00:33:14,440
I think there was some idea that that was a general phenomenon.

480
00:33:14,440 --> 00:33:16,080
But if you do some arithmetic, you

481
00:33:16,080 --> 00:33:18,680
get an interesting result. Suppose

482
00:33:18,680 --> 00:33:23,320
that each function in the brain occurred

483
00:33:23,320 --> 00:33:27,800
in 10 different places at random.

484
00:33:27,800 --> 00:33:32,240
Then if you removed half the brain,

485
00:33:32,240 --> 00:33:33,640
how many functions would you lose?

486
00:33:37,800 --> 00:33:40,880
Well, almost no arithmetic tells you

487
00:33:40,880 --> 00:33:44,560
you would lose about one part in 1,000.

488
00:33:44,560 --> 00:33:50,080
And so, in fact, you would never be able to detect it.

489
00:33:50,080 --> 00:33:54,520
So this idea that the brain has enormous redundancy

490
00:33:54,520 --> 00:33:57,640
will now change that number to five.

491
00:33:57,640 --> 00:34:00,560
Suppose each function is somewhat

492
00:34:00,560 --> 00:34:03,440
supported in five different parts of the brain.

493
00:34:03,440 --> 00:34:09,480
Then if you take off half the brain, then what am I saying?

494
00:34:09,480 --> 00:34:16,280
One part in 32, chance of losing some significant function.

495
00:34:16,280 --> 00:34:20,600
So probably lots of things that we do

496
00:34:20,600 --> 00:34:23,120
are supported in several parts of the brain.

497
00:34:23,120 --> 00:34:28,000
Apparently, the language center is pretty unique,

498
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:28,920
and some others.

499
00:34:28,920 --> 00:34:34,120
But be careful about the conclusions

500
00:34:34,120 --> 00:34:38,320
you read from optimistic neuroscientists.

501
00:34:47,520 --> 00:34:50,600
Anyway, Papert and I worked on this idea

502
00:34:50,600 --> 00:34:55,800
of how could these large numbers of different processes

503
00:34:55,800 --> 00:34:58,880
be organized.

504
00:34:58,880 --> 00:35:00,880
And we made various theories about it.

505
00:35:00,880 --> 00:35:08,800
And then around, I guess, the late 1970s,

506
00:35:08,800 --> 00:35:10,400
we stopped working together.

507
00:35:10,400 --> 00:35:14,400
And Papert developed his revolutionary ideas

508
00:35:14,400 --> 00:35:21,960
about education, which certainly have had a lot of influence,

509
00:35:21,960 --> 00:35:27,600
although they didn't sweep the world in the way we had hoped.

510
00:35:27,600 --> 00:35:31,680
And I kept working on the society of mind theory.

511
00:35:31,680 --> 00:35:35,520
And we didn't work together so much,

512
00:35:35,520 --> 00:35:41,200
but we still did plenty of criticizing

513
00:35:41,200 --> 00:35:42,480
and supporting of each other.

514
00:35:45,080 --> 00:35:49,240
Anyway, my theory ended up with this idea

515
00:35:49,240 --> 00:35:52,360
that is sort of based on Freud.

516
00:35:52,360 --> 00:35:56,040
I don't know if I kept a picture of his here.

517
00:35:57,880 --> 00:36:04,200
Freud concluded that the mind was an interesting arena,

518
00:36:04,200 --> 00:36:05,480
sort of.

519
00:36:05,480 --> 00:36:11,360
And he had the mind divided into three parts.

520
00:36:11,360 --> 00:36:14,840
At one end of the mind, which were inherited

521
00:36:14,840 --> 00:36:18,160
from most other animals, is called

522
00:36:18,160 --> 00:36:21,600
the id, which is a bunch of instinctive,

523
00:36:21,600 --> 00:36:25,960
mainly built-in behavioral mechanisms.

524
00:36:25,960 --> 00:36:32,440
And a second part of the mind is

525
00:36:32,440 --> 00:36:35,600
what he called the superego, which

526
00:36:35,600 --> 00:36:37,600
is a collection of critics.

527
00:36:37,600 --> 00:36:42,360
So in Freud's first image, the brain is in two parts.

528
00:36:42,360 --> 00:36:45,480
One is a set of instinctive, built-in behaviors.

529
00:36:45,480 --> 00:36:47,960
And the other is a set of critics,

530
00:36:47,960 --> 00:36:54,680
which actually are associated with a culture or, well,

531
00:36:54,680 --> 00:36:56,780
culture and a tradition.

532
00:36:56,780 --> 00:37:00,040
And you learn from other people things that are good to do

533
00:37:00,040 --> 00:37:02,360
and things that are bad to do.

534
00:37:02,360 --> 00:37:08,200
And that's called the superego.

535
00:37:08,200 --> 00:37:10,480
This is your set of values and standards

536
00:37:10,480 --> 00:37:13,920
and tests for suitable behavior.

537
00:37:13,920 --> 00:37:16,440
And the middle is this strange object

538
00:37:16,440 --> 00:37:22,480
called the ego, which is not what people think it is.

539
00:37:22,480 --> 00:37:24,600
At least Freud's word, the ego is

540
00:37:24,600 --> 00:37:27,400
a kind of big, neutral battleground

541
00:37:27,400 --> 00:37:35,040
where the instinctive behaviors I keep wanting to.

542
00:37:35,040 --> 00:37:37,640
Oh, you can see that arrow if I take my finger off it.

543
00:37:45,280 --> 00:37:49,980
And then gradually, as I kept trying

544
00:37:49,980 --> 00:37:52,460
to figure out how problems are solved

545
00:37:52,460 --> 00:37:57,100
and what kind of processes might be involved,

546
00:37:57,100 --> 00:38:00,780
I got this picture, which has six layers.

547
00:38:00,780 --> 00:38:04,860
And various people come around and say,

548
00:38:04,860 --> 00:38:08,620
I don't think you need to distinguish between layers

549
00:38:08,620 --> 00:38:11,140
four and five.

550
00:38:11,140 --> 00:38:16,340
Why don't you just lump all the three top layers into one?

551
00:38:16,340 --> 00:38:25,260
And I sort of laugh quietly and say,

552
00:38:25,260 --> 00:38:28,700
these people are trying to find a physics-like, unified,

553
00:38:28,700 --> 00:38:31,380
minimal theory of psychology.

554
00:38:31,380 --> 00:38:34,140
And they're probably right in one sense.

555
00:38:34,140 --> 00:38:36,320
But if they do that, they'll get stuck.

556
00:38:36,320 --> 00:38:39,460
Because if you get a new idea, there'll be no place to put it.

557
00:38:39,500 --> 00:38:47,420
So if you have something that's very mysterious,

558
00:38:47,420 --> 00:38:51,300
don't imitate the physicists.

559
00:38:51,300 --> 00:38:54,940
Because if you make a theory that's exactly right

560
00:38:54,940 --> 00:38:58,900
and just accounts for the data and there's nothing extra

561
00:38:58,900 --> 00:39:05,080
and nothing loose, then when you notice a new phenomenon,

562
00:39:05,080 --> 00:39:10,320
like dark matter, then the physicists

563
00:39:10,320 --> 00:39:12,480
don't know what to do.

564
00:39:12,480 --> 00:39:17,760
Should they regard dark matter as some obscure feature

565
00:39:17,760 --> 00:39:21,000
of spacetime, or does it have something

566
00:39:21,000 --> 00:39:24,240
to do with this universe being near another one

567
00:39:24,240 --> 00:39:26,480
that you can't otherwise communicate with?

568
00:39:26,480 --> 00:39:30,040
And it's all very puzzling.

569
00:39:30,040 --> 00:39:33,080
But there are lots of things that don't fit into Newton's

570
00:39:33,080 --> 00:39:35,040
laws these days.

571
00:39:35,040 --> 00:39:42,200
And I'm not suggesting a six-layer theory of physics,

572
00:39:42,200 --> 00:39:43,560
but it might be worth a try.

573
00:39:50,280 --> 00:39:52,600
OK, so what am I?

574
00:39:52,600 --> 00:40:03,760
I made up some nice slides, but I think I'll stop.

575
00:40:03,760 --> 00:40:05,600
So who has some questions?

576
00:40:05,600 --> 00:40:11,240
And what would you like to see in a theory of psychology?

577
00:40:11,240 --> 00:40:14,880
What do you want to be explained?

578
00:40:14,880 --> 00:40:21,200
A lot of people are convinced that there

579
00:40:21,200 --> 00:40:24,720
are some really serious problems and mysteries,

580
00:40:24,720 --> 00:40:26,720
like what is consciousness?

581
00:40:26,720 --> 00:40:36,880
And if you look at chapter 4, my feeling

582
00:40:36,880 --> 00:40:43,400
is consciousness is an etymological accident

583
00:40:43,400 --> 00:40:47,840
that people got a word, which is a suitcase for all

584
00:40:47,840 --> 00:40:49,400
of the things they don't understand

585
00:40:49,400 --> 00:40:51,280
about the mind and more.

586
00:40:52,280 --> 00:41:00,400
But once you've got a word and it goes in the culture,

587
00:41:00,400 --> 00:41:02,560
consider the word consciousness for a minute

588
00:41:02,560 --> 00:41:05,720
from a legal point of view.

589
00:41:05,720 --> 00:41:08,600
Suppose that you happen to be walking along,

590
00:41:08,600 --> 00:41:16,040
and you're carrying something.

591
00:41:16,040 --> 00:41:17,080
Where is that pointer?

592
00:41:17,440 --> 00:41:19,600
And it happens to stick somebody's eye out.

593
00:41:22,880 --> 00:41:29,480
Then it's very important when they sue you

594
00:41:29,480 --> 00:41:32,000
to establish whether you meant to do it

595
00:41:32,000 --> 00:41:36,200
or whether it was an accident.

596
00:41:36,200 --> 00:41:38,000
Did you consciously plan to?

597
00:41:42,680 --> 00:41:45,000
I can't think of the English word for it.

598
00:41:45,920 --> 00:41:47,480
I can't think of the English word

599
00:41:47,480 --> 00:41:50,160
for putting somebody's eye out.

600
00:41:50,160 --> 00:41:56,080
There's beheading and also gouges is a good word.

601
00:42:01,840 --> 00:42:08,120
So anyway, it's very important for social reasons

602
00:42:08,120 --> 00:42:13,320
to have a word for whether an action was deliberately

603
00:42:13,320 --> 00:42:18,400
violating the rules as opposed to accidentally violating

604
00:42:18,400 --> 00:42:23,360
the rules, like if you tripped on the stairs

605
00:42:23,360 --> 00:42:27,080
and landed on somebody and broke their neck.

606
00:42:27,080 --> 00:42:30,480
That's not a crime unless you were

607
00:42:30,480 --> 00:42:36,120
so clever as to make it appear that it was an accident.

608
00:42:36,120 --> 00:42:38,960
Anyway, you see what I mean?

609
00:42:38,960 --> 00:42:44,560
So our whole system of fairness and ethics

610
00:42:44,560 --> 00:42:47,880
and social responsibility is based

611
00:42:47,880 --> 00:42:51,460
on the distinction between whether an action was

612
00:42:51,460 --> 00:42:54,360
deliberate or not.

613
00:42:54,360 --> 00:43:01,240
And so did he do that consciously is a word for that.

614
00:43:01,240 --> 00:43:04,400
And somehow the idea of conscious became elevated.

615
00:43:04,400 --> 00:43:06,360
Well, that's a very superficial.

616
00:43:06,360 --> 00:43:09,280
You can probably think of 10 other reasons

617
00:43:09,280 --> 00:43:12,960
why a word like that.

618
00:43:12,960 --> 00:43:13,680
Yes?

619
00:43:13,680 --> 00:43:18,320
Yeah, Martin, sometimes in your writing,

620
00:43:18,320 --> 00:43:20,400
it seems to me that there's both sides of it.

621
00:43:20,400 --> 00:43:23,680
Sometimes you argue with both sides of it.

622
00:43:23,680 --> 00:43:26,360
It seems like in that kind of, I can well imagine

623
00:43:26,360 --> 00:43:28,080
there's that kind of representation.

624
00:43:28,080 --> 00:43:30,640
You have representation of self and representation

625
00:43:30,640 --> 00:43:31,920
of your mind.

626
00:43:31,920 --> 00:43:34,760
But then you say there's no self or no consciousness.

627
00:43:34,760 --> 00:43:36,880
Why can't you think about consciousness

628
00:43:36,880 --> 00:43:40,680
as just a process that is reasoning about your own mind?

629
00:43:40,680 --> 00:43:42,640
Is there a problem with that?

630
00:43:42,640 --> 00:43:44,760
I understand you don't want to talk about soul

631
00:43:44,760 --> 00:43:46,960
because that's a religious notion.

632
00:43:46,960 --> 00:43:50,160
No, but sometimes when you say conscious, that is,

633
00:43:50,160 --> 00:43:53,040
do you remember doing it?

634
00:43:53,040 --> 00:43:53,880
Which is?

635
00:43:53,880 --> 00:43:55,600
Yeah, but don't I load up my process

636
00:43:55,600 --> 00:44:00,160
that asks me what I think about my own mind?

637
00:44:00,160 --> 00:44:03,640
And then I retrieve that and I say, yeah, I do remember it.

638
00:44:03,640 --> 00:44:06,080
Well, you're right, actually.

639
00:44:06,080 --> 00:44:08,600
I went to a lot of trouble to find

640
00:44:08,600 --> 00:44:13,160
25 or 30 different uses for the word consciousness.

641
00:44:13,160 --> 00:44:17,360
And probably if one of us worked harder,

642
00:44:17,360 --> 00:44:19,000
we could take those and condense them

643
00:44:19,000 --> 00:44:23,600
into five or six much better ones that account for more

644
00:44:23,600 --> 00:44:24,720
stuff than the 30.

645
00:44:24,720 --> 00:44:27,280
Well, I think you've got five right there, ideas, goals,

646
00:44:27,280 --> 00:44:29,240
memory, thoughts, and feelings, right?

647
00:44:29,240 --> 00:44:31,000
That might be just right for something.

